Halve, peel and finely slice the @echalion shallot{1}. Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the cores and seeds. Chop into small pieces. Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1} in a #sieve{}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on medium heat. When hot, add the shallot and pepper and cook, stirring occasionally, until starting to soften, ~{2-3%minutes}. Stir in the @ground cumin{2} and @ground coriander{1}. Cook for ~{1%minute}. Stir in the @bulgur wheat{100} and chickpeas.

From your #kettle{} pour in the boiling @water{200%ml} and bring back to the boil. Pop a lid on the pan and remove from the heat. Leave to the side for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve (the bulgur will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(roughly chopped). Pick the @mint{1}(leaves picked from stalks) and roughly chop (discard the stalks). Zest the @lemon{1/2} then chop into wedges. Roughly chop the @walnuts{20}.

Five minutes before the bulgur is ready, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on high heat. When hot, add the @king prawns{150} and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch} and stir-fry until cooked, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Add a squeeze of @lemon juice{} to the pan and remove from the heat.

Fluff up the bulgur with a #fork{} and stir through the lemon zest, walnuts and half the mint and parsley. Season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed. Serve in bowls topped with the prawns, remaining herbs and any remaining lemon wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!